# What’s working well

- Clear layering / responsibilities
- Ticket, User, Comment as proper domain models with enums for Status, Priority, Role.
- TicketService handling all JSON persistence with Jackson (tickets.json in the working directory).
- UserService with a simple in-memory user list + “current user” concept (ready for a login screen later).
- Controllers:
- TicketApplication = entry point, loads main-view.fxml.
- MainViewController = main screen, table, filters, menu actions.
- TicketDialogController = create dialog.
- EditTicketDialogController = edit dialog + comments UI.
- Nice JavaFX touches
- TableView<Ticket> with:
- Custom date formatting for createdAt using DateTimeFormatter("yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm").
- Color-coded priorityColumn cells (HIGH=red-ish, MEDIUM=orange, LOW=green).
- Double-click on a row to open the edit dialog.
- A “status bar” label (saveIndicatorLabel) that reflects save state (“All Changes Saved” / unsaved).
- Persistence / ID handling
- TicketService:
- Loads all tickets on startup using Jackson + JavaTimeModule (so LocalDateTime is handled correctly).
- Writes pretty-printed JSON (SerializationFeature.INDENT_OUTPUT) to tickets.json.
- Generates numeric IDs by scanning existing IDs, finding max, and adding 1.
- Validates tickets before saving (title/status/priority must be present).
- Comments support
- Comment model with id, ticketId, content, createdBy, createdAt.
- Tickets can hold a List<Comment> and addComment() automatically sets ticketId.
- EditTicketDialogController:
- Has newCommentField, commentsListView.
- handleAddComment() creates a comment with the current user (or “Unknown”) and adds it to the ticket.
- Overall, this is already beyond a toy example — it’s a decent little desktop ticket system.
- 🔧 Things you could improve/refine
- Nothing is “wrong”, but here are sensible next refinements:
- Tighten responsibilities in MainViewController
- It currently:
- Handles UI interactions (good).
- Talks directly to TicketService and UserService.
- Implements filter logic, dialog launching, save/load, and a bit of error handling.
 -For a bigger app you’d eventually move:
 -Filtering logic into a dedicated service or utility (easier to unit test).
 -Some of the UI-independent bits (like constructing dialogs) into helper methods.
 -For now it’s fine, but it’s worth keeping in mind.
 -Error handling & user feedback

You already have showAlert(...) patterns in place — good.

In a few places you still e.printStackTrace() and log to stderr; you could:

Always show a user-friendly alert like “Could not load tickets.json – see logs for details.”

Optionally log with Logger consistently rather than printStackTrace().

Unused imports / dependencies

In MainViewController you still import ObjectMapper, SerializationFeature, JavaTimeModule, but you’ve moved JSON I/O to TicketService. Those imports can be culled.

In module-info.java you require:

requires org.controlsfx.controls;
requires com.dlsc.formsfx;
requires eu.hansolo.tilesfx;


If you’re not actually using those libraries, you can remove them to keep things cleaner.

File path for tickets.json

Currently TicketService uses:

private static final String FILE_PATH = "tickets.json";


That’s fine for a simple local app, but you might later:

Put it under a dedicated app directory (e.g. user.home + "/.ticket-tracker/tickets.json").

Or allow configuring the path (e.g. from a settings dialog).

UserService isn’t fully surfaced yet

UserService has roles and a concept of “current user”, but the current UI doesn’t show a login screen or user switching.

That’s not a problem — it just means you’ve got a nice hook for a “v2” feature.

Testing

There are no unit tests (yet).

Easy wins:

Tests for TicketService (save/load, ID generation, validation).

Tests for Ticket comment handling logic.

Tests for filtering logic (extracted into a pure helper method).